\section{Solutions}

\subsection{Problem 1.1}

\vspace{2mm}

\begin{mdframed}[style=jradduemmdbox, frametitle = \textbf{Problem 1.1} (Recurrence)] Suppose a sequence $\{a_n\}$ (with $n \geq 1$) of positive integers satisfy $a_0 = 8$ and $a_1 = 30,$ and for $n \geq 2,$ $a_n = 8a_{n-1} - 15a_{n-2}$. Find the remainder of $a_{2020}$ divided by 7.

\end{mdframed}

\ans{$5$}

\sol Let us first find the closed form of $a_n$.By characteristic equations, $$r^2 = 8r - 15 \Longleftrightarrow r^2 - 8r + 15 = (r-5)(r-3) = 0.$$ This implies that $a_n = A\cdot5^n + B\cdot3^n $ where $A$ and $B$ are numerical coefficients. To find these coefficients, we use the values of $a_1$ and $a_0$ and solve it by system of equations:

\begin{equation*}
    \begin{cases}
    30 = 5A+3B & \qquad (1) \\ 8 = A + B & \qquad (2)
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}

In order to solve for $(A,B)$, we multiply the (2) second equation by 5, then subtract it by the (1) first equation. As a result, we get that $B=5$. 

Substituting $B$ with 5 in the (2) second equation, we get that $A=3$. This implies that $a_n = 3\cdot5^n + 5\cdot3^n.$ Evaluating $a_{2020} \pmod{7}$ gives the following:

\vspace{-3mm}

\begin{equation*}
    \begin{array}{lllll}
        3 \cdot 5^{2020} +   5 \cdot 3^{2020} 
           & \equiv & 3 \cdot 5^{4} +   5 \cdot 3^{4} & \pmod{7} & \text{\footnotesize{(By Fermat's Little Theorem)}}\\
   
           
           & \equiv & 3 \cdot 25^{2} +   5 \cdot 9^{2} & \pmod{7} & \\
         
           
           & \equiv & 48 +   20 & \pmod{7} & \\
           
            & \equiv & 68 & \pmod{7} & \\
            
             & \equiv & \boxed{5} & \pmod{7} & \\
    \end{array}
\end{equation*}

\subsection{Problem 1.2}

\vspace{2mm}

\begin{mdframed}[style=jradduemmdbox, frametitle = \textbf{Problem 1.2} (Diophantine equations)]  Find all $(x,y)\in\mathbb{Z},$ such that $x^2 +4y^2 -2xy-2x-4y-8=0$.

\end{mdframed}

\ans{$(3,5)$,$(3,-1)$}

\sol The equation can be rewritten into the following:

\vspace{-3mm}

\begin{equation*}
    \begin{array}{lll}
     \hspace{21mm}  x^2 - 4xy + 4y^2 -2xy -2x -4y - 8  & =& 0 - 4xy  \\
       
       \hspace{21mm} (x-y)^2 + 2xy -2x -4y - 8  & =& 0   \\
         
         \hspace{12mm} (x-y)^2 + 2(xy -x -2y +2) - 12  & =& 0   \\
         
        \hspace{28mm}  (x-y)^2 + 2(x-2)(y-1)   & =& 12   \\
    \end{array}
\end{equation*}
 
Since we are looking for integer pairs $(x,y)$ then we can divide the problem into three cases.



\joshbf{\raggedright  Case \# 1:} If both $x$ and $y$ are positive, then only $\boxed{(3,5)}$ can satisfy.

\vspace{1mm}

\joshbf{\raggedright  Case \# 2:} If both $x$ and $y$ are negative, no solution can suffices the condition.


\vspace{1mm}

\joshbf{\raggedright  Case \# 3:} If one of the variables in $(x,y)$ is negative or non-negative (and vice versa), then $\boxed{(3,-1)}$ can satisfy.

\boxed{$\therefore$ Only $(3,5)$ and $(3,-1)$ can satisfy the equation. }


